<div class="container-fluid bg-light">
     <div class="container page-content">
        <h2 class="font-weight-bold text-dark"  style="margin:20px 0;padding:20px 0;">How the Recognition Process Works, Step by Step</h2>
        <p>Five steps separate the American diploma from the Bulgarian recognition certificate. Two take place in the United States, three in Bulgaria, and all of them can be arranged remotely.</p>
    
       
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-1 orange border-bottom font-weight-bold"><p class="h2">01</p></div>
            <div class="col-md-11 border-bottom">
                <p class="mb-0 font-weight-bold">The diploma and the official transcript from the school</p>
                <p>Upon graduation, ONSITES High School issues the U.S. high school diploma and an official transcript listing every course taken, the credits earned, and the grades under the American system. The courses carry the official course numbers of the Florida Department of Education, which allows the Bulgarian commission to trace the content of the schooling subject by subject. These two documents form the foundation of the entire procedure and are issued in English with the school's certification.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-1 orange border-bottom font-weight-bold"><p class="h2">02</p></div>
            <div class="col-md-11 border-bottom">
                <p class="mb-0 font-weight-bold">Apostille from the State of Florida</p>
                <p>The United States and Bulgaria are both parties to the Hague Convention, and no bilateral treaty waives legalization between the two countries, so the diploma and the transcript receive an apostille. For documents issued in Florida, the competent authority is the Florida Department of State. The apostille certifies the authenticity of the signatures and seals on the school documents and enables NACID to verify them through official channels. The certification is arranged by mail or courier, without traveling to the United States.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-1 orange border-bottom font-weight-bold"><p class="h2">03</p></div>
            <div class="col-md-11 border-bottom">
                <p class="mb-0 font-weight-bold">Certified translation into Bulgarian</p>
                <p>The diploma, the transcript, and the affixed apostilles are translated into Bulgarian by a sworn translator, whose signature is certified according to the established procedure. The translation must render the student's names exactly as they appear in the identity document, a seemingly small detail that ranks among the most frequent reasons files are returned. Established translation agencies in Sofia handle American school documents routinely and finish within a few business days.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-1 orange border-bottom font-weight-bold"><p class="h2">04</p></div>
            <div class="col-md-11 border-bottom">
                <p class="mb-0 font-weight-bold">Filing the application with NACID</p>
                <p>The standard application form is filed together with the documents in person at the NACID administrative service center in Sofia, 52A Dr. G. M. Dimitrov Blvd., open every business day from 8:00 a.m. to 6:30 p.m., or fully electronically through the e-services portal with scanned documents attached. The state fee is paid at filing according to the current price list. The file receives a reference number under which its status can be tracked online at any time.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-1 orange border-bottom font-weight-bold"><p class="h2">05</p></div>
            <div class="col-md-11 border-bottom">
                <p class="mb-0 font-weight-bold">Commission decision and certificate</p>
                <p>The NACID expert commission decides within one month from the date all documents are presented; if additions are requested, the clock pauses until they are supplied. The issued certificate confirms equivalence with Bulgarian secondary education, and the grades are converted to the Bulgarian six-point scale, for which NACID also maintains an official calculator. The certificate has no expiry date and is entered in the public Register of Recognized Secondary Education, where any institution can verify it.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>